                <h2 id="usage-examples">Usage examples</h2>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">SQL join: risks by type and tier</h3>
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>SELECT r.Id,
       r.Title,
       rt.Name  AS RiskType,
       tier.Name AS RiskTier,
       r.RiskScore,
       r.BusinessArea
FROM   Risks r
       INNER JOIN RiskRiskTypes rrt ON rrt.RiskId = r.Id
       INNER JOIN RiskTypes rt ON rt.Id = rrt.RiskTypeId
       LEFT JOIN RiskTiers tier ON tier.Id = r.RiskTierId
WHERE  r.IsDeleted = 0
ORDER BY r.RiskScore DESC;</pre>
                </div>
                <p class="small text-muted">This mirrors the API projection, demonstrating how multi-select risk types surface alongside tier data for cross-cutting analysis.</p>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">SQL join: actions with provenance</h3>
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>SELECT a.Id,
       a.Title,
       a.Status,
       src.Name       AS ActionSource,
       r.Title        AS RelatedRisk,
       i.Title        AS RelatedIssue,
       m.Title        AS RelatedMilestone
FROM   Actions a
       LEFT JOIN ActionSources src ON src.Id = a.ActionSourceId
       LEFT JOIN RiskActions ra ON ra.ActionId = a.Id
       LEFT JOIN Risks r ON r.Id = ra.RiskId
       LEFT JOIN IssueActions ia ON ia.ActionId = a.Id
       LEFT JOIN Issues i ON i.Id = ia.IssueId
       LEFT JOIN MilestoneActions ma ON ma.ActionId = a.Id
       LEFT JOIN Milestones m ON m.Id = ma.MilestoneId
WHERE  a.IsDeleted = 0;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">API workflow: build a risk register extract</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Call <code>GET /api/v1/risks?pageSize=100</code> to fetch risks with embedded classification data.</li>
                    <li>Call <code>GET /api/v1/actions?status=in_progress</code> to retrieve open mitigations and their <code>ActionSource</code>.</li>
                    <li>Join both datasets in your reporting tool using risk identifiers to present mitigation progress by theme.</li>
                </ol>

                <div class="inset-text mt-4">
                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Reporting tip:</strong> When consuming the API from Power BI or similar tooling, honour the pagination metadata (<code>totalPages</code>, <code>currentPage</code>) and request data in batches to stay within rate limits.</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-5">Getting projects with all related data</h3>
                <p>Projects are central entities that link to many other tables. Here's how to retrieve a complete project view:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get a project with all basic information
SELECT p.Id,
       p.ProjectCode,
       p.Title,
       p.Aim,
       p.StrategicObjectives,
       p.StartDate,
       p.TargetDeliveryDate,
       p.ActualDeliveryDate,
       p.RagStatus,
       p.RagJustification,
       p.PathToGreen,
       p.Status,
       p.IsFlagship,
       p.IsAiInitiative,
       pl.Name AS Phase,
       bal.Name AS BusinessArea,
       dp.Name AS DeliveryPriority,
       u.Name AS PrimaryContactName,
       u.Email AS PrimaryContactEmail
FROM Projects p
LEFT JOIN PhaseLookups pl ON pl.Id = p.PhaseId
LEFT JOIN BusinessAreaLookups bal ON bal.Id = p.BusinessAreaId
LEFT JOIN DeliveryPriorities dp ON dp.Id = p.DeliveryPriorityId
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = p.PrimaryContactUserId
WHERE p.IsDeleted = 0
  AND p.Id = @@ProjectId;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project milestones</h3>
                <p>Milestones are linked to projects via the <code>ProjectId</code> foreign key. A project can have multiple milestones:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all milestones for a project with progress tracking
SELECT m.Id,
       m.Name,
       m.Description,
       m.BaselineDueDate,
       m.DueDate,
       m.ActualDate,
       m.Status,
       m.ProgressPercent,
       m.ExternalRef,
       m.Notes,
       CASE 
           WHEN m.ActualDate IS NOT NULL AND m.ActualDate <= m.DueDate THEN 'On Time'
           WHEN m.ActualDate IS NOT NULL AND m.ActualDate > m.DueDate THEN 'Late'
           WHEN m.DueDate < GETUTCDATE() AND m.Status != 'complete' THEN 'Overdue'
           ELSE 'Upcoming'
       END AS MilestoneStatus
FROM Milestones m
WHERE m.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
  AND m.IsDeleted = 0
ORDER BY m.DueDate ASC;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project monthly updates</h3>
                <p>Monthly updates are stored in <code>ProjectMonthlyUpdates</code> with a one-to-many relationship to <code>MonthlyUpdateNarratives</code> for multiple narrative entries per month:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get monthly updates for a project with all narrative entries
SELECT pmu.Id,
       pmu.ProjectId,
       pmu.Year,
       pmu.Month,
       pmu.Narrative AS MainNarrative,
       pmu.CreatedByName,
       pmu.CreatedByEmail,
       pmu.CreatedAt,
       pmu.UpdatedAt,
       pmu.SubmittedAt,
       -- Count of individual narrative entries
       (SELECT COUNT(*) 
        FROM MonthlyUpdateNarratives mun 
        WHERE mun.ProjectMonthlyUpdateId = pmu.Id) AS NarrativeCount
FROM ProjectMonthlyUpdates pmu
WHERE pmu.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY pmu.Year DESC, pmu.Month DESC;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get individual narrative entries for a specific monthly update
SELECT mun.Id,
       mun.ProjectMonthlyUpdateId,
       mun.Narrative,
       mun.CreatedByName,
       mun.CreatedByEmail,
       mun.CreatedAt
FROM MonthlyUpdateNarratives mun
WHERE mun.ProjectMonthlyUpdateId = @@ProjectMonthlyUpdateId
ORDER BY mun.CreatedAt ASC;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project successes</h3>
                <p>Project successes are stored in two tables: <code>ProjectSuccesses</code> for general success records, and <code>ProjectWeeklySuccessUpdates</code> for weekly success updates:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all success records for a project
SELECT ps.Id,
       ps.ProjectId,
       ps.SuccessDescription,
       ps.RecordedByEmail,
       ps.RecordedByName,
       ps.RecordedAt,
       ps.IsReportedToSlt,
       ps.SltResponse,
       ps.SltRespondedByEmail,
       ps.SltRespondedByName,
       ps.SltRespondedAt
FROM ProjectSuccesses ps
WHERE ps.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY ps.RecordedAt DESC;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get weekly success updates for a project
SELECT pwsu.Id,
       pwsu.ProjectId,
       pwsu.Year,
       pwsu.WeekNumber,
       pwsu.WeekStartDate,
       pwsu.WeekEndDate,
       pwsu.SuccessDescription,
       pwsu.CreatedByName,
       pwsu.CreatedByEmail,
       pwsu.CreatedAt,
       pwsu.IsReportedToSlt,
       pwsu.SltResponse,
       pwsu.SltRespondedByEmail,
       pwsu.SltRespondedByName,
       pwsu.SltRespondedAt
FROM ProjectWeeklySuccessUpdates pwsu
WHERE pwsu.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY pwsu.Year DESC, pwsu.WeekNumber DESC;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project status updates and RAG history</h3>
                <p>Projects track status changes through <code>ProjectStatusUpdates</code> and RAG status history through <code>ProjectRagHistories</code>:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all status updates for a project
SELECT psu.Id,
       psu.ProjectId,
       psu.Narrative,
       psu.CreatedByUserId,
       u.Name AS CreatedByName,
       u.Email AS CreatedByEmail,
       psu.CreatedAt
FROM ProjectStatusUpdates psu
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = psu.CreatedByUserId
WHERE psu.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY psu.CreatedAt DESC;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get RAG status history for a project
SELECT prh.Id,
       prh.ProjectId,
       prh.RagStatus,
       prh.ChangedAt,
       prh.ChangedBy
FROM ProjectRagHistories prh
WHERE prh.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY prh.ChangedAt DESC;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project contacts and roles</h3>
                <p>Projects have multiple contact relationships stored in various tables:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all project contacts
SELECT pc.Id,
       pc.ProjectId,
       pc.UserId,
       u.Name AS ContactName,
       u.Email AS ContactEmail,
       pc.Email AS ContactEmailDirect,
       pc.Role,
       pc.TeamStatus,
       pc.SortOrder
FROM ProjectContacts pc
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = pc.UserId
WHERE pc.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY pc.SortOrder, pc.Role;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get project role assignments (SRO, Service Owner, PMO Contact, etc.)
SELECT 
    'SRO' AS RoleType,
    psro.Id,
    psro.ProjectId,
    u.Name AS UserName,
    u.Email AS UserEmail
FROM ProjectSeniorResponsibleOfficers psro
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = psro.UserId
WHERE psro.ProjectId = @@ProjectId

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Service Owner' AS RoleType,
    pso.Id,
    pso.ProjectId,
    u.Name AS UserName,
    u.Email AS UserEmail
FROM ProjectServiceOwners pso
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = pso.UserId
WHERE pso.ProjectId = @@ProjectId

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'PMO Contact' AS RoleType,
    ppc.Id,
    ppc.ProjectId,
    u.Name AS UserName,
    u.Email AS UserEmail
FROM ProjectPmoContacts ppc
LEFT JOIN Users u ON u.Id = ppc.UserId
WHERE ppc.ProjectId = @@ProjectId

ORDER BY RoleType, UserName;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Getting project RAID items</h3>
                <p>Projects are linked to Risks, Issues, Actions, and Milestones through foreign keys:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all RAID items for a project
SELECT 
    'Risk' AS ItemType,
    r.Id,
    r.Title,
    r.RiskScore,
    r.Status,
    r.ImpactRating,
    r.LikelihoodRating
FROM Risks r
WHERE r.ProjectId = @@ProjectId AND r.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Issue' AS ItemType,
    i.Id,
    i.Title,
    NULL AS RiskScore,
    i.Status,
    NULL AS ImpactRating,
    NULL AS LikelihoodRating
FROM Issues i
WHERE i.ProjectId = @@ProjectId AND i.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Action' AS ItemType,
    a.Id,
    a.Title,
    NULL AS RiskScore,
    a.Status,
    NULL AS ImpactRating,
    NULL AS LikelihoodRating
FROM Actions a
WHERE a.ProjectId = @@ProjectId AND a.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Milestone' AS ItemType,
    m.Id,
    m.Name AS Title,
    NULL AS RiskScore,
    m.Status,
    NULL AS ImpactRating,
    NULL AS LikelihoodRating
FROM Milestones m
WHERE m.ProjectId = @@ProjectId AND m.IsDeleted = 0

ORDER BY ItemType, Title;</pre>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Understanding junction tables</h3>
                <p>Junction tables enable many-to-many relationships between entities. Here's how they work:</p>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">RiskRiskTypes junction table</h4>
                <p>The <code>RiskRiskTypes</code> table allows a single risk to be classified with multiple risk types. This is a many-to-many relationship:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all risk types for a specific risk
SELECT r.Id AS RiskId,
       r.Title AS RiskTitle,
       rt.Id AS RiskTypeId,
       rt.Name AS RiskTypeName,
       rt.Code AS RiskTypeCode,
       rrt.CreatedAt AS ClassificationDate
FROM Risks r
INNER JOIN RiskRiskTypes rrt ON rrt.RiskId = r.Id
INNER JOIN RiskTypes rt ON rt.Id = rrt.RiskTypeId
WHERE r.Id = @@RiskId
  AND r.IsDeleted = 0
  AND rt.IsActive = 1
ORDER BY rt.Name;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="inset-text mt-3">
                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>How it works:</strong> The <code>RiskRiskTypes</code> table has a composite primary key on (<code>RiskId</code>, <code>RiskTypeId</code>), ensuring each risk-type combination is unique. When a risk is deleted, all its risk type associations are automatically removed (cascade delete).</p>
                </div>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">RiskActions, IssueActions, MilestoneActions junction tables</h4>
                <p>These junction tables link RAID items to their associated actions:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all actions linked to a risk
SELECT a.Id AS ActionId,
       a.Title AS ActionTitle,
       a.Status AS ActionStatus,
       a.Priority AS ActionPriority,
       a.DueDate AS ActionDueDate,
       ra.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Actions a
INNER JOIN RiskActions ra ON ra.ActionId = a.Id
WHERE ra.RiskId = @@RiskId
  AND a.IsDeleted = 0
ORDER BY a.DueDate;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all risks, issues, and milestones linked to an action
SELECT 
    'Risk' AS SourceType,
    r.Id AS SourceId,
    r.Title AS SourceTitle,
    ra.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Risks r
INNER JOIN RiskActions ra ON ra.RiskId = r.Id
WHERE ra.ActionId = @@ActionId AND r.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Issue' AS SourceType,
    i.Id AS SourceId,
    i.Title AS SourceTitle,
    ia.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Issues i
INNER JOIN IssueActions ia ON ia.IssueId = i.Id
WHERE ia.ActionId = @@ActionId AND i.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Milestone' AS SourceType,
    m.Id AS SourceId,
    m.Name AS SourceTitle,
    ma.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Milestones m
INNER JOIN MilestoneActions ma ON ma.MilestoneId = m.Id
WHERE ma.ActionId = @@ActionId AND m.IsDeleted = 0

ORDER BY SourceType, SourceTitle;</pre>
                </div>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">MilestoneRisks and MilestoneIssues junction tables</h4>
                <p>These tables link milestones to risks and issues that affect them:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all risks and issues affecting a milestone
SELECT 
    'Risk' AS ItemType,
    r.Id AS ItemId,
    r.Title AS ItemTitle,
    r.RiskScore,
    r.Status,
    mr.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Risks r
INNER JOIN MilestoneRisks mr ON mr.RiskId = r.Id
WHERE mr.MilestoneId = @@MilestoneId AND r.IsDeleted = 0

UNION ALL

SELECT 
    'Issue' AS ItemType,
    i.Id AS ItemId,
    i.Title AS ItemTitle,
    NULL AS RiskScore,
    i.Status,
    mi.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Issues i
INNER JOIN MilestoneIssues mi ON mi.IssueId = i.Id
WHERE mi.MilestoneId = @@MilestoneId AND i.IsDeleted = 0

ORDER BY ItemType, ItemTitle;</pre>
                </div>

                <h4 class="h6 mt-3">ProjectObjectives, ProjectProducts, ProjectMissions junction tables</h4>
                <p>These tables link projects to objectives, products, and missions:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all objectives linked to a project
SELECT o.Id AS ObjectiveId,
       o.Title AS ObjectiveTitle,
       o.Status AS ObjectiveStatus,
       po.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM Objectives o
INNER JOIN ProjectObjectives po ON po.ObjectiveId = o.Id
WHERE po.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
  AND o.IsDeleted = 0
ORDER BY o.Title;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get all products linked to a project
SELECT pp.Id AS ProjectProductId,
       pp.ProductFipsId,
       pp.CreatedAt AS LinkCreatedAt
FROM ProjectProducts pp
WHERE pp.ProjectId = @@ProjectId
ORDER BY pp.ProductFipsId;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="inset-text mt-3">
                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Junction table pattern:</strong> All junction tables follow the same pattern: they contain foreign keys to the two entities being linked, often with a composite primary key, and include audit timestamps (<code>CreatedAt</code>). This allows tracking when relationships were established and supports many-to-many relationships between entities.</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Complete project dashboard query</h3>
                <p>Here's a comprehensive query to get all project information in one result set:</p>
                
                <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 mb-3">
                    <pre>-- Get complete project dashboard data
SELECT 
    p.Id,
    p.ProjectCode,
    p.Title,
    p.RagStatus,
    p.Status,
    p.StartDate,
    p.TargetDeliveryDate,
    -- Counts
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Milestones m WHERE m.ProjectId = p.Id AND m.IsDeleted = 0) AS MilestoneCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Risks r WHERE r.ProjectId = p.Id AND r.IsDeleted = 0) AS RiskCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Issues i WHERE i.ProjectId = p.Id AND i.IsDeleted = 0) AS IssueCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Actions a WHERE a.ProjectId = p.Id AND a.IsDeleted = 0) AS ActionCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ProjectMonthlyUpdates pmu WHERE pmu.ProjectId = p.Id) AS MonthlyUpdateCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ProjectSuccesses ps WHERE ps.ProjectId = p.Id) AS SuccessCount,
    (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM ProjectWeeklySuccessUpdates pwsu WHERE pwsu.ProjectId = p.Id) AS WeeklySuccessCount,
    -- Latest update
    (SELECT TOP 1 pmu.Year, pmu.Month 
     FROM ProjectMonthlyUpdates pmu 
     WHERE pmu.ProjectId = p.Id 
     ORDER BY pmu.Year DESC, pmu.Month DESC) AS LatestMonthlyUpdate,
    -- Phase and business area
    pl.Name AS Phase,
    bal.Name AS BusinessArea
FROM Projects p
LEFT JOIN PhaseLookups pl ON pl.Id = p.PhaseId
LEFT JOIN BusinessAreaLookups bal ON bal.Id = p.BusinessAreaId
WHERE p.IsDeleted = 0
  AND p.Id = @@ProjectId;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="inset-text mt-3">
                    <p class="mb-0"><strong>Performance tip:</strong> For large datasets, consider using separate queries for counts and aggregations rather than subqueries, or use a reporting view that pre-calculates these values. Indexes on foreign keys (<code>ProjectId</code>, <code>RiskId</code>, etc.) are essential for query performance.</p>
                </div>

